<a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec3.p4" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec3.p4"></a><p>We first analyzed the influence of depleted neurogenesis on habituation to a novel environment, which is considered a simple form of spatial recognition measured by a decrease over time in exploratory activity as the context loses its novelty. Hippocampal dysfunction impairs this form of spatial recognition and delays habituation, which results in increased locomotor activity in the novel environment <a href="#pone.0001959-Gray1">[38]</a>. In this task, bigenic-Dox mice were not impaired showing similar novelty-induced locomotor activity than bigenic-vehicle mice (<a href="#pone-0001959-g005">Figure 5A</a>; group effect: F<sub>1,10</sub> = 1.25, p&gt;0.28; interaction group√ótime: F<sub>11,110</sub> = 0.71, p&gt;0.72).</p>
